  "prompt": "What is the difference between a grade of A+ and an A at the University of Illinois?",
  "response": "At the University of Illinois, the grading scale is as follows:\n\n- A+: 4.00\n- A: 4.00\n- A-: 3.67\n- B+: 3.33\n- B: 3.00\n- B-: 2.67\n- C+: 2.33\n- C: 2.00\n- C-: 1.67\n- D+: 1.33\n- D: 1.00\n- D-: 0.67\n- F: 0.00\n\nAs you can see, both A+ and A grades are assigned a grade point value of 4.00. The difference between an A+ and an A at the University of Illinois is primarily symbolic, as they carry the same grade point value. However, an A+ might be used to recognize exceptional work within the context of the course, even though it does not provide any additional grade point advantage over an A.",
